is not and cannot be held accountable.

@endnode

@node SuppliedFiles "Supplied Files"

All source to CyberCron is included in the Source/* directory.  Please do
not redistribute changes you make.  Instead, send them to me for inclusion
in the master distribution.

The s directory contains a sample crontab file.  This is the one I am
currently using on my system.  It contains a number of comments that give
some helpful hints on how to use some of the more advanced features of
CyberCron.

In RexxScripts is CCShow.rexx, based on the NCShow.rexx script that came with
@{"NazCron" link NazCron}.  It will call @{"LIST_EVENTS" link RCmdListEvents} and if there are active events, it will
loop through the list calling @{"SHOW_EVENT" link RCmdShowEvent} to display each one.

Also in the rexx directory you will find the files at.rexx and batch.rexx.
These are the files Loren Rittle sent me that implement the UNIX @{"at" link AtCommand}
and @{"batch" link BatchCommand} commands using CyberCron.  They have since
been updated by Graham Walter to be much more complete.

The Catalogs directory is where @{"translation catalogs" link Localization} for languages that
CyberCron has been converted to are found.  If you are running under
Workbench 2.1 and would like to use CyberCron in your language, copy the
appropriate file into your LOCALE:Catalogs/<language> directory.

@endnode

@node DefineCron "What is a cron?"

A cron is a program that runs in the background (i.e., requires no user
intervention) and executes commands at specific times, as defined in a
@{"crontab file" link CronTabFile}.  It allows the automation of jobs that one runs regularily.

For example, many maintenance tasks can be handled by a cron event.
Incremental system backups to a streaming tape could be started at a time
when one is generally away from the machine every day or every week, for
example.  Or you might have a cron entry run a script that logs onto BIX,
CompuServe, or wherever and downloads all your mail and unread messages
automatically during the night when rates are lower.

A cron can also be used as a means of reminding yourself to do things.  You
might add an event that runs an alarm clock program in the morning to wake
you up, for example.  Or you might have it throw a requester up telling you
to go to bed when it is getting late.  The possibilities are endless.

@endnode

@node WhyCyberCron "Why another cron for the Amiga?"

There have been several crons for the Amiga already.  These include
AmiCron, dcron, TPTCron and @{"NazCron" link NazCron}, to name a few.  So what's the
need for yet another cron?

CyberCron was written to take advantage of the new features of Workbench
2.04 (or greater), and thus has many advanced options that previous crons
don't.  It's this new functionality that makes switching over to CyberCron
worthwhile.

CyberCron uses the new System() call in dos.library to launch events.  This
call is far superior to the Execute() call of Workbench 1.3 days which the
other crons use.  Through the use of the System() call, CyberCron can
support options such as the stack size or priority to launch specific
events at.

CyberCron also understands ARexx.  It can start events as ARexx commands
and/or scripts.  It also has an ARexx port which can accept a number of
@{"ARexx commands" link RexxPort} to control it while running.

CyberCron supports @{"localization" link Localization}.  If you are running it on a machine with
locale.library and have a translation catalog for your local language,
CyberCron's messages will appear in your language instead of English.

Finally, CyberCron also uses @{"file notification" link FileNotification} to determine when the
crontab file has been changed.  This eliminates the performance hit that
previous Amiga crons have suffered from due to the fact that they had to
check the crontab file for updates once a minute.

@endnode

@node StartingUp "Starting CyberCron"
@next CronTabFile

You can start CyberCron from either the CLI or Workbench.

When CyberCron is started from the Workbench, it trys to clone a copy of
the Workbench's CLI structure.  What this means is that the command path
that existed at the time LoadWB was run will be propagated on to commands
CyberCron launches.

CyberCron understands the following arguments:

    [@{" CRONTAB " link ArgCronTab} <filespec>] [@{" LOGFILE " link ArgLogFile} <filespec>]
    [@{" DEFSTACK " link ArgDefStack} <Default Stack>] [@{" DEFPRI " link ArgDefPriority} <Default Priority>]
    [@{" SENDMAIL " link ArgSendMail} <"{command} {from switch} %s {name switch} *"%s*"">]
    [@{" CRONPRI " link ArgCronPriority} <Cron's Priority>] [@{" PORTNAME " link ArgPortName} <ARexx Portname>]

All arguments are optional.  If not specified, CyberCron will use an
appropriate default.  See the specific options' documentation for more
information.

To use these options from a Workbench icon, simply make each tooltype be in
the form of <option>=<setting>.  For example, if you wanted to specify a
logfile of T:CronLog, you would have a tooltype that looked like

	LOGFILE=T:CronLog

@endnode

##############################################################################
##      These nodes are for the various command line argument links         ##
##############################################################################

@node ArgCronTab "The »CronTab« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp
@prev ArgPortName

This specifies the @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile} that CyberCron will try and read.  If not
specified, s:CronTab will be used as the default.

The crontab file may also be changed while CyberCron is running by using
the @{"NEW_EVENT_FILE" link RCmdNewEventFile} ARexx command.

TEMPLATE
	CRONTAB/K

EXAMPLE
	CronTab cron:ctab

@endnode

@node ArgLogFile "The »LogFile« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp

This indicates where CyberCron is to log activities.  If no filespec is
given, logging will be turned off.

The logfile may also be changed while CyberCron is running by using the
@{"NEW_LOG_FILE" link RCmdNewLogFile} ARexx command.

TEMPLATE
	LOGFILE/K

EXAMPLE
	LogFile T:CronLog

@endnode

@node ArgSendMail "The »SendMail« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp

CyberCron supports sending the output of a command it has launched to a
user via e-mail.  For this to work, however, it needs to know how to send
mail on the local system.  This command tells CyberCron how to do this.

If the sendmail option is not specified then entries which try to direct
their output to e-mail will not be able to.  File @{"output redirection" link EArgReDirOut} will
be honored instead.

The argument for this command should be in the form of

    "<sendmail command> <from switch> %s <realname switch> *"%s*""

For example, for AmigaUUCP's sendmail one would use

    "UUCP:c/SendMail -f %s -R *"%s*""

For CyberCron to be able to send mail, the sendmail command must read the
mail message from its standard input.  This is because CyberCron sets up a
pipe to redirect output into sendmail.  This also means that you must have
@{"PIPE:" link PipeDevice} mounted before mail can be sent.

The sendmail command must also expect the To: and Subject: fields to be in
its input instead of on the command line, and must generate the Message-ID:
field itself.

AmigaUUCP's SendMail command meets all the above criteria.

TEMPLATE
	SENDMAIL/K

EXAMPLE
	SendMail "UUCP:c/SendMail -f %s -R *"%s*""

@endnode

@node ArgDefStack "The »DefStack« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp

This is the default stack size to launch executables with.  Values less
than 2048 will be rejected.

This argument is ignored when launching ARexx events.

If not specified, the stack size that CyberCron was started with will be
used as the default.

TEMPLATE
	DEFSTACK/K/N

EXAMPLE
	DefStack 25000

@endnode

@node ArgDefPriority "The »DefPri« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp

This specifies the default priority to launch executables at.

This option is ignored by ARexx events.

If not specified, this option defaults to zero.

TEMPLATE
	DEFPRI/K/N

EXAMPLE
	DefPri -1

@endnode

@node ArgCronPriority "The »CronPri« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp

This is the priority that CyberCron should run at.

If not specified, this option defaults to no change.  I.e., CyberCron will
remain that the priority it was started at.

ToolPri is accepted as an alias for CronPri.  This is for conformity with
the @{"Style Guide" link StyleGuide}.

TEMPLATE
	TOOLPRI=CRONPRI/K/N

EXAMPLE
	CronPri 4

@endnode

@node ArgPortName "The »PortName« command line argument"
@toc StartingUp
@next ArgCronTab

This option specifies the ARexx portname that CyberCron will use.

If not specified, CyberCron defaults to a portname of CYBERCRON.

CyberCron will not let you start it multiple times with the same port name.
It does, however, support the use of concurrent CyberCron tasks which each
have their own portname.

Using this option, one could have multiple crontab files.  One might also
choose to have one CyberCron task that handles their @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile} while
a second is used as a server for script commands such as the @{"at" link AtCommand} command.

TEMPLATE
	PORTNAME/K

EXAMPLE
	PortName CyberCronAtServer

@endnode

##############################################################################
##      End of nodes describing the various command line arguments          ##
##############################################################################

@node CronTabFile "Creating a crontab file"
@prev StartingUp
@next RexxPort

Lines in this file must be blank, a comment, or an event.  Comments are
denoted by lines that start with a "#" symbol.  Events take the form of

	min hour day month dow command <command's args, if any>

in their simplest form.  Each of min, hour, day, month and dow (day of the
week) are specifications for what range of values this command is to be run
at.  A * indicates any value is acceptable.  Numeric digits specify
specific values and can be seperated by a , (seperates distinct entries) or
a - (used to indicate a range of entries).  For example,

	* * * * * Date

would run the command date every minute of every hour of every day of every
month regardless of the day of the week.

	0 * * * * Date

is similar, but only runs the date command on the zeroth minute of each
hour.

	1,5-10,25 * * * * Date

would run the date command on minutes 1, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 and 25 of each
hour.

Months range from 1 (January) to 12 (December).  The day of the week ranges
from 0 (Sunday) to 6 (Saturday).

CyberCron also supports a number of extensions to the traditional event
format.  These may occur anywhere in the event, and are:

    @{" :NAME " link EArgName} <name>
    @{" < " link EArgReDirIn} <filespec>
    @{" > " link EArgReDirOut} <filespec>
    @{" 2> " link EArgReDirErr} <filespec>
    @{" :MAILUSER " link EArgMailUser} <user name>
    @{" :EXECONCE " link EArgExecOnce}
    @{" :OBEYQUEUE " link EArgObeyQueue} <queue name>
    @{" :NOLOG " link EArgNoLog}
    @{" :REXX " link EArgRexx}
    @{" :STACK " link EArgStack} <bytes>
    @{" :PRI " link EArgPriority} <priority>
    @{" :CUSTOMSH " link EArgCustomShell} <shell name>
    @{" :SYSSH " link EArgSystemShell}

Please note that these above options are parsed with the dos.library
ReadArgs() command.  Because of this, those options which take a variable
must have whitespace between the option's keyword and its assignment.  This
generally isn't a problem, except that most people I know are used to
specifying redirection as

	@{">" link EArgReDirOut}ram:foo

while the proper method for CyberCron would be

	@{">" link EArgReDirOut} ram:foo

The other implication of using ReadArgs() is that quotes will be stripped
out, as will extra spaces.  To retain spaces, you must inclose the element
they proceed or follow with quotes.  For example, one might use

	date @{">" link EArgReDirOut} "Ram:Two  Spaces"

To retain quotes, you will have to quote the argument as you would for
spaces, but escape a quote character withing the quoted string.  For
example.

	"This has a *" quote in it"


There is one aditional special case that needs to be observed when creating
an event.  If the command you are running is actually a script _and_ it
contains a space in it's filename, you must explicitly call the AmigaDOS
Execute command for it to work.  For example, you'd have to use

	execute "foo bar script"

instead of

	"foo bar script"

(those people with WShell who want to execute an ARexx script from a WShell
context would use WShell's Rexx command instead of Execute.)

This is due to a problem that the AmigaDOS shell has executing script's
whose command name has been quoted.  This only applies to scripts which
have spaces in their name, so very few people should be affected by this
limitation.

@endnode

##############################################################################
##             These nodes descibe the various event options                ##
##############################################################################

@node EArgName "The »:NAME« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile
@prev EArgSystemShell

Specifies the formal name the event will be known under when CyberCron is
accessed via its @{"ARexx port" link RexxPort}.

You may use the same name multiple time.  However, this is not recommened.

TEMPLATE
	:NAME/K

EXAMPLE
	:Name WakeMeUp

@endnode

@node EArgReDirIn "The input redirection event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

This specifies where input is to be redirected from.

TEMPLATE
	</K

EXAMPLE
	< "CON:0/0/300/100/Gimme some input"

@endnode

@node EArgReDirOut "The output redirection event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

Specifies where output is to be redirected to.

If >> is used instead of >, the filespec will be appended to instead of
overwritten.

TEMPLATE
	>/K or >>/K

EXAMPLES
	> RAM:job.out
	>> RAM:job.logfile

@endnode

@node EArgReDirErr "The error redirection event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

Specifies where standard error is to be redirected to.

If 2>> is used instead of 2>, the filespec will be appended to instead of
overwritten.

Note that this is currently ignored by the event launcher per a discussion
I had with Randell Jesup.  Standard error support wasn't really finished
for 2.0, and that makes it difficult to support this at this time.

TEMPLATE
	2>/K or 2>>/K

EXAMPLES
	2> RAM:job.err
	2>> RAM:job.errlog

@endnode

@node EArgMailUser "The »:MAILUSER« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

Specifies a user to send mail to with the output of the command being run.
If the @{"SENDMAIL" link ArgSendMail} command line option was not specified, this will be ignored
when the event is started, and any @{"output redirection" link EArgReDirOut} specified will be
used, instead.

The username may be any e-mail address, so mail can be sent to both local
and remote systems.  If your sendmail supports it, you could even specify
an alias and have it send mail to multiple people.

TEMPLATE
	:MAILUSER/K

EXAMPLE
	:MailUser root

@endnode

@node EArgExecOnce "The »:EXECONCE« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

After the event has been started, remove it from the event list.

TEMPLATE
	:EXECONCE/S

EXAMPLE
	:ExecOnce

@endnode

@node EArgObeyQueue "The »:OBEYQUEUE« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

Select a specific queue to schedule the event under.  See the section on
@{"queues" link JobQueues} for more information.

Using this, @{":EXECONCE" link EArgExecOnce}, @{":MAILUSER" link EArgMailUser} and some ARexx macros, one could simulate
the @{"at" link AtCommand} and @{"batch" link BatchCommand} commands under UNIX.  (See Loren's @{"at" link AtCommand} stuff for an
example of how.)

TEMPLATE
	:OBEYQUEUE/K

EXAMPLE
	:ObeyQueue c

@endnode

@node EArgNoLog "The »:NOLOG« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

If you specified a @{"logfile" link ArgLogFile} then every time an event is started or ends a
message gets sent to the log file.  This turns off logging for the specific
event.  Handy for things one runs many, many times, in keeping the size of
your logfile from exploding.

TEMPLATE
	:NOLOG/S

EXAMPLE
	:NoLog

@endnode

@node EArgRexx "The »:REXX« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

Start this command using ARexx rather than trying to run it as a system
call.  If the first character of the command is "`" then it will be started
as an ARexx string rather than a command.

TEMPLATE
	:REXX/S

EXAMPLE
	:Rexx

@endnode

@node EArgStack "The »:STACK« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

The stacksize to use when launching the event.

This option is ignored for ARexx events.

If the value specified is less than 2048, or this option is omitted, then
the @{"default stack size" link ArgDefStack} will be used instead.

TEMPLATE
	:STACK/K/N

EXAMPLE
	:Stack 50000

@endnode

@node EArgPriority "The »:PRI« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

The priority to launch the event at.

This option is ignored for ARexx events.

If this option is omitted then the @{"default priority" link ArgDefPriority} will be used.

TEMPLATE
	:PRI/K/N

EXAMPLE
	:PRI -5

@endnode

@node EArgCustomShell "The »:CUSTOMSH« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile

Use a specific custom shell when launching the event.  See your "Using the
System Software" manual for more information on custom shells.

This option is ignored by ARexx events.

TEMPLATE
	:CUSTOMSH/K

EXAMPLES
	:CustomSH WShell
	:CustomSH BootShell

@endnode

@node EArgSystemShell "The »:SYSSH« event line option"
@toc CronTabFile
@next EArgName

If no custom shell is specified, CyberCron will try and launch the command
using the specified User Shell.  If you do not want the User Shell to be
used for a specific event, specifying this flag will cause CyberCron to use
the system shell.

This option is ignored by ARexx events.

TEMPLATE
	:SYSSH/S

EXAMPLE
	:SysSH

@endnode

##############################################################################
##           End of nodes descibing the various event options               ##
##############################################################################

@node RexxPort "CyberCron as an ARexx Function Host"
@prev CronTabFile
@next JobQueues

CyberCron's default ARexx port name is CYBERCRON.  However, this can be
changed with the @{"PORTNAME" link ArgPortName} command line option.

CyberCron supports the following ARexx commands:

    @{" SHUTDOWN " link RCmdShutdown}
    @{" VERSION " link RCmdVersion}
    @{" SUSPEND " link RCmdSuspend}
    @{" RESUME " link RCmdResume}
    @{" NEW_EVENT_FILE " link RCmdNewEventFile} <filespec>
    @{" CLOSE_EVENT_FILE " link RCmdCloseEventFile}
    @{" NEW_LOG_FILE " link RCmdNewLogFile} <filespec>
    @{" CLOSE_LOG_FILE " link RCmdCloseLogFile}
    @{" SHOW_STATUS " link RCmdShowStatus}
    @{" PURGE_REXX_EVENTS " link RCmdPurgeRexxEvents}
    @{" ADD_EVENT " link RCmdAddEvent} <event>
    @{" DELETE_REXX_EVENT " link RCmdDeleteRexxEvent} <event name>
    @{" DELETE_EVENT " link RCmdDeleteEvent} <event name>
    @{" LIST_EVENTS " link RCmdListEvents}
    @{" SHOW_EVENT " link RCmdShowEvent} <event name>
    @{" SET_QUEUE_MAX " link RCmdSetQueueMax} <queue name> <max jobs executable at a time>
    @{" GET_QUEUE_MAX " link RCmdGetQueueMax} <queue name>
    @{" EVENT_NEXT_EXEC " link RCmdEventNextExec} <event name>
    @{" NEXT_EVENT_TO_EXEC " link RCmdNextEventToExec}
    @{" EXPAND_SSSC " link RCmdExpandSSSC} <seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation}>
    @{" SSSC_TO_ASCII " link RCmdSSSCtoASCII} <seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation}>

@endnode

##############################################################################
##            These nodes describe the various ARexx commands               ##
##############################################################################

@node RCmdShutdown "The »SHUTDOWN« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort
@prev RCmdSSSCtoASCII

Causes CyberCron to quit.  Can also be accomplished by sending a break
signal to CyberCron.

Once SHUTDOWN is started, CyberCron will not accept any more ARexx
commands.

It may take a while for CyberCron to actually quit, however, because it
must wait for any currently running events to terminate.

QUIT is accepted as a synonym of SHUTDOWN to provide comformity with the
@{"Style Guide" link StyleGuide}.

TEMPLATE
	QUIT=SHUTDOWN

EXAMPLES
	Shutdown
	Quit

@endnode

@node RCmdVersion "The »VERSION« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Returns the version, revision and date of CyberCron in the form

    <version>.<revision> (<day>.<month>.<year>)

This is returned in the RESULT string, so you must issue an @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults}
command before you can use this command.

TEMPLATE
	VERSION

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} Version
	say result

@endnode

@node RCmdSuspend "The »SUSPEND« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Stop processing events.  @{"File notifcation" link FileNotification} on the @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile}
remains active, however, so changes will be processed normally.

TEMPLATE
	SUSPEND

EXAMPLE
	Suspend

@endnode

@node RCmdResume "The »RESUME« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Resume processing of events after a @{"SUSPEND" link RCmdSuspend} has been issued.

TEMPLATE
	RESUME

EXAMPLE
	Resume

@endnode

@node RCmdNewEventFile "The »NEW_EVENT_FILE« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Change the @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile} to <filespec>.  This checks to make sure the file
actually exists before making the change.  However, parse errors will not
be noticed until the current crontab has been purged and CyberCron actually
starts reading the new file.

If something goes wrong (crontab file not found or its name is too long)
which doesn't cause the previous crontab file to have been purged yet then
this will return RC_WARN (5).

If a fatal error occurs (couldn't restart @{"notification" link FileNotification} on the new file)
and the previous crontab has been purged, but the new one not read in, this
will return RC_ERROR (10).

TEMPLATE
	NEW_EVENT_FILE FILESPEC/A

EXAMPLE
	New_Event_File S:CronTab2

@endnode

@node RCmdCloseEventFile "The »CLOSE_EVENT_FILE« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Free all entries from the @{"CronTab" link ArgCronTab}.  Processing of entries added by the
ARexx @{"ADD_EVENT" link RCmdAddEvent} command will still continue.  Use @{"NEW_EVENT_FILE" link RCmdNewEventFile} to read a
@{"crontab file" link CronTabFile} again, if you so desire.

TEMPLATE
	CLOSE_EVENT_FILE

EXAMPLE
	Close_Event_File

@endnode

@node RCmdNewLogFile "The »NEW_LOG_FILE« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Changes the @{"logfile" link ArgLogFile} to <filespec>.

If an error occurs (the new name is too long, for example) then RC_WARN (5)
will be returned and the old logfile, if specified, will remain active.

TEMPLATE
	NEW_LOG_FILE FILESPEC/A

EXAMPLE
	New_Log_File T:CronLog

@endnode

@node RCmdCloseLogFile "The »CLOSE_LOG_FILE« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Turns off logging.  You can re-enable logging with the @{"NEW_LOG_FILE" link RCmdNewLogFile}
command, if you so desire.

TEMPLATE
	CLOSE_LOG_FILE

EXAMPLE
	Close_Log_File

@endnode

@node RCmdShowStatus "The »SHOW_STATUS« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Returns a couple bits of information about CyberCron's status.  This is in
the form of

    @{"<activity>" link RCmdSuspend} @{"<crontab filespec>" link ArgCronTab} @{"<logfile filespec>" link ArgLogFile}

where <activity> is either ACTIVE or SUSPENDED.

TEMPLATE
	SHOW_STATUS

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} Show_Status
	say result

@endnode

@node RCmdPurgeRexxEvents "The »PURGE_REXX_EVENTS« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

All events added with the ARexx @{"ADD_EVENT" link RCmdAddEvent} command will be purged.
Processing of entries from the @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile} will continue normally.

TEMPLATE
	PURGE_REXX_EVENTS

EXAMPLE
	Purge_Rexx_Events

@endnode

@node RCmdAddEvent "The »ADD_EVENT« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Adds an event to CyberCron's active list.  Use the same format as if you
were specifying an event in a @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile}.  Comments are not allowed.

If an error occurs in parsing the event, RC_ERROR (10) will be returned.

TEMPLATE
	ADD_EVENT EVENT/A

EXAMPLE
	ADD_EVENT '0 8 * * 1-5 Echo "Go to work!" @{">" link EArgReDirOut} CON:0/0/200/50/Hey!/CLOSE/WAIT'

@endnode

@node RCmdDeleteRexxEvent "The »DELETE_REXX_EVENT« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Deletes the specified event, but only if it is was added with the ARexx
@{"ADD_EVENT" link RCmdAddEvent} command.

If the event was not found, RC_ERROR (10) will be returned.

TEMPLATE
	DELETE_REXX_EVENT @{"EVENT_NAME/A" link InternalNaming}

EXAMPLE
	Delete_Rexx_Event 'the event'

@endnode

@node RCmdDeleteEvent "The »DELETE_EVENT« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Same as @{"DELETE_REXX_EVENT" link RCmdDeleteRexxEvent}, but can be used to delete any event, even those
read from the @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile}.

If the event was not found, RC_ERROR (10) will be returned.

TEMPLATE
	DELETE_EVENT @{"EVENT_NAME/A" link InternalNaming}

EXAMPLE
	Delete_Event 'the event'

@endnode

@node RCmdListEvents "The »LIST_EVENTS« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Returns a list of all the current events CyberCron is tracking, seperated
by spaces.  Note that the events are listed using CyberCron's internal
@{"naming scheme" link InternalNaming}.

The result is returned in a result string, so you must use @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults}
before calling this command, or you will get an error.

If there are no events, then the string "<None>" is returned.  If an error
occured, an empty string will be returned.

TEMPLATE
	LIST_EVENTS

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} List_Events
	say result

@endnode

@node RCmdShowEvent "The »SHOW_EVENT« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Returns the full specification for the specified event, as it would be
given in a @{"crontab file" link CronTabFile}, except that it will have the event's @{"internal name" link InternalNaming}
prepended.

Note that events may not look exactly the same as when they were added.
This is because CyberCron converts events into an internalized structure
and unconverts them when this command is called.

If the event was not found then an empty string will be returned.

You must specify @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults} before using this command, or you will get
an error.

TEMPLATE
	SHOW_EVENT @{"EVENT_NAME/A" link InternalNaming}

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} Show_Event 'the event'
	say result

@endnode

@node RCmdSetQueueMax "The »SET_QUEUE_MAX« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Set's the maximum number of jobs that may be run under the specified queue
at any given time.

If an illegal queue name is specified, RC_ERROR (10) will be returned.

Setting the maximum to zero is legal, and will result in no jobs for the
specified queue being executed until such a time as the queue maximum is
raised to greater than zero again.

See the section on @{"queues" link JobQueues} for more information.

TEMPLATE
	SET_QUEUE_MAX QUEUE_NAME/A MAX_JOBS_EXECUTABLE_AT_A_TIME/N/A

EXAMPLE
	Set_Queue_Max a 3

@endnode

@node RCmdGetQueueMax "The »GET_QUEUE_MAX« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Get the current maximum number of jobs that can be run under the specified
queue at any given time.

If an illegal queue name is specified, -1 is returned.

See the section on @{"queues" link JobQueues} for more information.

TEMPLATE
	GET_QUEUE_MAX QUEUE_NAME/A

EXAMPLE
	GET_QUEUE_MAX a

@endnode

@node RCmdEventNextExec "The »EVENT_NEXT_EXEC« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

Returns the next time at which the specified event will execute at.
This is returned as the number of seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation}.

If the event cannot be found, a null string will be returned.

CyberCron will look up to seven years into the future trying to find a time
that satisfies the requirements of the event's timespec.  This is to allow
for the effect of leap years.

If CyberCron cannot determine a time at which the event would next execute,
zero will be returned.

The result is returned in a result string, so you must use @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults}
before calling this command, or you will get an error.

TEMPLATE
	EVENT_NEXT_EXEC @{"EVENT_NAME/A" link InternalNaming}

EXAMPLE
	Event_Next_Exec 'the event'

@endnode

@node RCmdNextEventToExec "The »NEXT_EVENT_TO_EXEC« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

This will scan through the event list, looking for the event that is due up
for execution next.  It returns a string in the form of

	@{"<event name>" link InternalNaming} <SSSC>

The <SSSC> field is the seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation} that the event will
execute at.

If no event is found then the string "<None>" will be returned.

The result is returned in a result string, so you must use @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults}
before calling this command, or you will get an error.

TEMPLATE
	NEXT_EVENT_TO_EXEC

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} Next_Event_To_Exec
	nextevent = result
	if (nextevent ~= '<None>') then
		parse var nextevent event sssc .

@endnode

@node RCmdExpandSSSC "The »EXPAND_SSSC« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort

This command will take the number of seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation} and
expand it into seperate fields for seconds, minutes, etc.  The result is
returned in a string in the form of

	<sec> <min> <hour> <day> <month> <year> <day of the week>

This is useful for scripts that want to make decisions based on the results
of @{"EVENT_NEXT_EXEC" link RCmdEventNextExec} or @{"NEXT_EVENT_TO_EXEC" link RCmdNextEventToExec}.

The result is returned in a result string, so you must use @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults}
before calling this command, or you will get an error.

TEMPLATE
	EXPAND_SSSC SECONDS_SINCE_@{"SYSTEM_CREATION" link SystemCreation}/A

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} @{"Next_Event_To_Exec" link RCmdNextEventToExec}
	nextevent = result
	if (nextevent ~= '<None>') then do
		parse var nextevent event sssc .
		Expand_SSSC sssc
		parse var result sec min hour day month year dow .
	end
		
@endnode

@node RCmdSSSCtoASCII "The »SSSC_TO_ASCII« ARexx command"
@toc RexxPort
@next RCmdShutdown

This command will take the number of seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation} and
return a human readable ASCII date string.

This is useful for scripts that want to display the results of @{"EVENT_NEXT_EXEC" link RCmdEventNextExec}
or @{"NEXT_EVENT_TO_EXEC" link RCmdNextEventToExec} to the user.

The result is returned in a result string, so you must use @{"OPTIONS RESULTS" link OptionsResults}
before calling this command, or you will get an error.

TEMPLATE
	SSSC_TO_ASCII SECONDS_SINCE_@{"SYSTEM_CREATION" link SystemCreation}/A

EXAMPLE
	@{"options results" link OptionsResults}
	address @{"CYBERCRON" link ArgPortName} @{"Next_Event_To_Exec" link RCmdNextEventToExec}
	nextevent = result
	if (nextevent ~= '<None>') then do
		parse var nextevent event sssc .
		@{"Show_Event" link RCmdShowEvent} event
		eventDisp = result
		if (eventDispl ~= '') then do
			say '->' || eventDisp
			SSSC_To_ASCII sssc
			say '  next execution at" result
		end
	end

@endnode

##############################################################################
##          End of nodes describing the various ARexx commands              ##
##############################################################################

@node JobQueues "How job queues work in CyberCron"
@prev RexxPort

CyberCron supports 26 job queues, named 'a' through 'z'.  Each queue has a
maximum number of jobs associated with it.  If an event has a queue
specified, not only must it be the appropriate time to run that event, but
the number of events currently running under that queue must be less than
the maximum allowed for the queue for the event to actually be executed.

Events that don't specify an @{":OBEYQUEUE" link EArgObeyQueue} argument are run under the default
queue (not included in the 26 named queues that are user accessable), which
allows an unlimited number of jobs to be executed at the same time.

All job queues are initilized with their maximum number of events to
execute set to one.  ARexx commands exist to @{"read" link RCmdGetQueueMax} and @{"change" link RCmdSetQueueMax} the maximum
number for specific queues.

Jobs that could not be started because the queue maximum would be exceeded
are marked as delayed.  They will be run the next time the queue is
available, regardless of whether or not their time spec matches the current
time they are up for scheduling.

Job queues were originally added to support writting ARexx scripts that
simulate the UNIX @{"at" link AtCommand} and @{"batch" link BatchCommand} commands.  However, I've tried to make
the interface flexible and useful in other areas.  For example, queues can
be used to insure sequencing of events.  Make sure that the queue you will
use has its maximum set to one (which is the default for all queues).
Specify when the first job is to run.  Specify that the second job should
run one minute after the first job.  If the first job is still running when
the second comes up for scheduling, the second job will be delayed.
CyberCron will check every minute after that to see if the first job has
completed and will run the second job when it is safe.  Any number of jobs
could be sequenced together using a queue in this manner.

@endnode

@node InternalNaming "The internal naming scheme used by CyberCron"

CyberCron's @{"LIST_EVENTS" link RCmdListEvents} command will return event names in an internalized
format.  These names are in the form of 0x???????? where ? indicates a hex
digit.  This is done so that events that have no formal name can be
specified from ARexx.  It also allows events to be specified unambigously,
which is useful if you have more than one event with the same formal name
and you wish to delete/show/etc a specific one.  To prevent naming
conflicts, CyberCron will not let you specify a formal name that begins
with the characters 0x (or 0X, as the case of the "x" doesn't matter).

When asking CyberCron to delete/show/etc an event, you can either use its
internal name, or, if it has a formal name, you may use that.  Internal
names are cumbersome to use by hand, and are impractical to handle except by
using console snap or under the control of an ARexx script.  Formal names
are much easier to deal with, which is why they are present.  If you wanted
to add a quick test event, you might give it a formal name of TestEvent and
then use that to delete it instead of having to figure out it's internal
name and then using it to delete the event.

@endnode

@node Localization "How to make CyberCron speak your language"

When running under Workbench 2.1, CyberCron has the ability to use a
translation catalog which contains the text strings it uses in a different
language.  These translation files are stored in the user's
LOCALE:Catalogs/<language> directory.  For example, the French string
catalog for CyberCron would be the file:

	LOCALE:Catalogs/français/CyberCron.catalog

Please note that case is important for the filename portion of the above
filespec.

It is also possible to make a Catalogs sub-directory in the directory where
the CyberCron executable resides.  This reduces the amount of clutter in
the user's LOCALE: volume.  If you placed the CyberCron executable in
SYS:WBStartup, then the corresponding location of the French catalog would
be:

	SYS:WBStartup/Catalogs/français/CyberCron.catalog

If there isn't a translation file for your language present in this
distribution (and there most likely won't be as I don't know any foreign
languages :->), you can make your own.  To do this, you need to:

	1) edit the dummy.ct file in the Source directory, translating
	   it as appropriate.  you should be looking at the
	   Source/CyberCronStrings.cd file as you do this since it
	   contains many important notes about what the different
	   strings are used for.

	2) run CatComp (a Commodore developer tool which I can't include)
	   to make the actual catalog that CyberCron will use.  For
	   example:

		catcomp Source/CyberCronStrings.cd <language>.ct catalog
		    locale:Catalogs/<language>/CyberCron.catalog

		(the above is all on one CLI line, of course)

If you don't have access to CatComp then feel free to @{"e-mail" link CAW} me your
translation (lha and uuencode it, though, or any special accent marks, etc,
will be lost) and I'll run it through CatComp.  I'd like any translation
files people come up with, anyway, so I can distribute them with future
versions of CyberCron.  Also, if you feel that one of the currently
available translation files has something which could be translated in a
better way, feel free to mail me those changes as well.

@endnode

@node ChangeLog "The history of CyberCron"
@next Credits

Version 1.0 -- Initial release

Version 1.1 -- Maintenance release the day after 1.0 was released.
               Don't remember what it fixed, though... :-)

@{" Version 1.2 " link Change1p2}

@{" Version 1.3 " link Change1p3}

@{" Version 1.4 " link Change1p4}

@{" Version 1.5 " link Change1p5}

@endnode

##############################################################################
##             Start of nodes describing CyberCron revisions                ##
##############################################################################

@node Change1p2 "Changes in version 1.2 of CyberCron"
@toc ChangeLog
@prev Change1p5

It has been pointed out to me that I forgot to specify the default rexx
extension of ".rexx".  Thus, scripts in the form of

	foo.rexx

would not be started unless you actually stated @{":REXX" link EArgRexx} foo.rexx instead of
being able to use @{":REXX" link EArgRexx} foo alone.

Also added a semaphore lock in the GetJobNum()/FreeJobNum() routines to
prevent the job table from possibly being clobbered by EndSystemJob()
getting called at the same time CyberCron was trying to start another job.

@endnode

@node Change1p3 "Changes in version 1.3 of CyberCron"
@toc ChangeLog

It has been requested that CyberCron become sensitive to small changes
backwards in time.  This is usually caused by reloading the system clock
from the battery backed clock once a day (as the battery backed clock tends
to keep better time on some machines).  Before running the event scan,
CyberCron will now check to see if time has gone backwards and will delay
event scans until it reaches the next minute that it would have actually
run a scan at if the time hadn't shifted backwards.  There is a 5 minute
threshhold limit, however, so if time goes backwards more than that (for
instance, daylight savings time changes state and you go back an hour) then
CyberCron assumes you know what you are doing and will use the new time
without delay.

I also switched the static declarations of struct RDArgs to
AllocDosObject()/FreeDosObject() pairs.  This should help insure that
CyberCron will run on any future versions of the OS, even if it will be a
few eons before I actually would have had to worry about this... :-)

@endnode

@node Change1p4 "Changes in version 1.4 of CyberCron"
@toc ChangeLog

Fixed handling of commands with a space in them.  Previously, they would be
indicated as not found.  Now they will work correctly.  Also modified the
log output a bit to indicate the command name portion of the command.  The
command is quoted with »« characters.

When CyberCron is first started, it will now spit an "I'm alive" message
out to the logfile.  Brian Vargyas wanted this so he could tell when his
BBS had rebooted by reading through the log.

CyberCron now checks to see if it is already running and will exit
gracefully if so.  Added new @{"PORTNAME" link ArgPortName} option to startup arguments to allow
multiple CyberCrons to be run if needed by specifying different ARexx port
names for each.

Modified CCShow.rexx to accept one argument when started to be used as the
portname to address.  This allows one to easly display the active jobs for
any CyberCron task running.  If no portname is specified, CCShow defaults
to CYBERCRON, which is CyberCron's @{"PORTNAME" link ArgPortName} default.

Aliased the @{"CRONPRI" link ArgCronPriority} startup option to TOOLPRI to try and be a bit more
comformant with the @{"Style Guide" link StyleGuide}.  Similarily, QUIT is now recognized as a
synonym for the @{"SHUTDOWN" link RCmdShutDown} ARexx command.

Because CyberCron now officially supports multiple copies of itself
running, I have made it use a public locking mechanism for the @{"logfile" link ArgLogFile}.
This way, one can have the same logfile for all instances of CyberCron and
not have to worry about it getting clobbered.  The job number list is also
shared between concurrent CyberCrons as well.

Documentation redone as an AmigaGuide file.  The hypertext nature of
AmigaGuide makes it a lot easier to navigate around the CyberCron
documentation and find information quickly.

Mike Sinz has provided me with wb2cli.o, a linker object that creates a CLI
structure for me when CyberCron is started from the Workbench.  This allows
CyberCron to propagate the path that existed at LoadWB time to jobs it
starts.

Updated the ErrorMsg() function to throw up an EasyRequester when CyberCron
is started from the WorkBench.  This was done because there is no StdErr to
write errors to in this case.  Once CyberCron is up and fully running,
ErrorMsg() calls will not use a requester, however.  At this point, only
things like "Crontab changed, re-reading" are sent to ErrorMsg().  Since
these are also sent to the Log() routine, the information isn't lost and it
allows CyberCron to remain non-interactive.

Added @{"localization" link Localization} support.  Now I need to find people to translate the
string catalog to other languages for me... :-)

Enhanced the WBtoCLIargs() routine.  Specifically, it now calls FindArg()
on each tooltype to decide if it should copy the tooltype over into the
argument string.  This prevents ReadArgs() from seeing arguments it doesn't
know about and generating a "wrong number of arguments" error.  This was
done to make it possible to include tooltypes such as DONOTWAIT in
CyberCron's .info file.  This makes it easy to drop CyberCron in one's
WBStartup drawer.

Modified the lmkfile to run source code through the indent filter.  This
helps make the code look a bit nicer by cleaning up comments as well as
insuring that the proper indentation levels are in use.

By popular demand, removed the ANSI control sequences from the startup and
help messages.

Noticed the Amiga2Date() function in utility.library.  Changed
GetSystemTime() to make use of it, saving 350+ bytes of code.

Found and squashed an Enforcer hit that would occur in DoMsg() when a
routine wanted to return a null string.

Added four new ARexx commands.  Two, @{"EVENT_NEXT_EXEC" link RCmdEventNextExec} and @{"NEXT_EVENT_TO_EXEC" link RCmdNextEventToExec},
deal with determining the time at which an event will execute at.  Both
return their results as the number of seconds since @{"system creation" link SystemCreation}.
To make dealing with this result easier, the @{"EXPAND_SSSC" link RCmdExpandSSSC} and @{"SSSC_TO_ASCII" link RCmdSSSCtoASCII}
commands were added.

Updated CCShow.rexx to display the time each job is next scheduled to
execute at by using the new @{"EVENT_NEXT_EXEC" link RCmdEventNextExec} and @{"SSSC_TO_ASCII" link RCmdSSSCtoASCII} Rexx commands.

If OwnDevUnit.library is present, CyberCron will now try and obtain a lock
on LOG-UPDATE.LOCK before trying to write to its logfile.  This will
protect its log updates from AmigaUUCP's trimfile executable.  For this to
work properly, however, you must be using v2.1 or better of
OwnDevUnit.library.

In previous versions of CyberCron, if a @{"queue" link JobQueues} was already executing the
maximum number of jobs it was set to and more jobs were due to be
scheduled, then only the first job would be delayed and the rest would be
skipped.  Now all such jobs will be delayed.

Recompiled under SAS/C 6.0.

@endnode

@node Change1p5 "Changes in version 1.5 of CyberCron"
@toc ChangeLog
@next Change1p2

Implemented some suggestions that Martin Taillefer sent me.  Specifically:

	Fixed the documentation to refer to Workbench ?.? instead of
	KickStart ?.?, which is the proper terminology.

	Removed the OC_BuiltInLanguage tag from the OpenCatalog() call
	since this is the default prodided by locale.library anyway.

	Eliminated MySPrintf() and now use sprintf() from amiga.lib since
	it's smaller.

	Removed some checks before freeing items in the cleanup code since
	as of V37 things like CloseLibrary(), FreeVec(), etc, all let you
	free things that weren't previously allocated.

	Modified the aborting of timer I/O so that the Disable()/Enable()
	are no longer used.

Got the new version of CatComp.  Fixed CyberCron to compile using it.
Reduces the size of the executable by about 300 bytes due to removal of
many unneeded reloc-32's.

For @{"v1.4" link Change1p4}, I made the routine that starts system jobs always enclose the
command name in quotes.  It has been brought to my attention that this
breaks many scripts.  As of v1.5, CyberCron no longer places quotes around
the command name indiscriminately.  Quotes are now inserted only when the
command name actually has a space in it.

@endnode

##############################################################################
##              End of nodes describing CyberCron revisions                 ##
##############################################################################

